    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.\n\nWhen using typed-`memoryview`s that are byte strings, would like to copy-convert them to `bytes` (or `bytearray`) objects with a simple assignment.\n\n\n### Describe the solution you'd like.\n\nHere is some simplified code that shows the intended behavior\n\n```cython\ncpdef bytes mv_to_bytes(const unsigned char[::1] mv):\n    cdef bytes b = mv\n    return b\n```\n\n### Describe alternatives you've considered.\n\nCurrently one could work around this by accessing the pointer from the typed-`memoryview` and then assign it to `bytes`. This will then perform a C-string copy construction of the `bytes` object\n\n```cython\ncpdef bytes mv_to_bytes(const unsigned char[::1] mv):\n    cdef const unsigned char* p = &mv[0]\n    cdef bytes b = p\n    return b\n```\n\nHowever this comes with a few pitfalls:\n\n1. `strlen` is used to determine the length when the length is already known\n2. If the string is not `\\0` terminated, this would have undefined behavior and/or crash.\n3. (From David) Non-contiguous typed `memoryviews` are incorrectly treated as contiguous\n\n\n<hr>\n\nOne could alternatively call `bytes` or `PyBytes_FromObject`/`PyBytes_AsStringAndSize` on the object directly. While this always possible (even with the C-string), Cython already does a nice job of handling conversion to/from C-strings and various Python string objects. This just seems like a good common case that would be helpful to include.\n\n### Additional context\n\nHere is a similar discussion around going from typed-`memoryview` objects to C/C+ objects:\n\n* https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/6750\n\nThis can also be extended to `str`s\n\n* https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/7584",
